<author><name><![CDATA[Quietust]]></name></author>
<updated>2006-02-09T15:44:01-07:00</updated>
<published>2006-02-09T15:26:22-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=1071&amp;p=9357#p9357</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=1071&amp;p=9357#p9357"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[NTSC NES Composite Video Levels]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=1071&amp;p=9357#p9357"><![CDATA[
Using that formula, "pure red" ($x6) lies at 70.45 degrees (expected 90), "pure green" ($xA) lies at 207.72 degrees (expected 210), and "pure blue" ($x2) lies at 314.08 degrees (expected 330). These "pure colors" are based on the phases darkened by the 'color de-emphasis' bits (assuming that they were meant to be pure red, green, and blue).<br /><br />I suppose these differences are due to the fact that neither YIQ nor YUV seem to represent all of the colors in an "evenly spaced" manner (that, or the conversion matrices have subtle amounts of error in them).<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=7">Quietust</a> — Thu Feb 09, 2006 3:26 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
